CONTENT: Here's some ideas to consider   1. How about if you have a complete natural language voice interface?    Similar to Chatgpt Advance Voice that's available in Chatgpt app in mobile.   Speech to text --> RAG ---> Text to Speech   You can consider eleven labs models for the text to speech, and something like Deepgram models for speech to text.   2. Memory   How do you manage memory for each prompt?   Does each question remember the last question?   I would encourage you try and implement different memory feature, even if it's temporary, at least some short term memory. Later on, you can have long term and permanent memory   3. Consider making agentic, so, it's available on Claude Desktop, Claude, etc.   Consider the frameworks I used in the roll dice app.   4. Once you have a memory feature in your bot, in your response, generate suggested prompts / follow up question.   That allows users to respond like "ok" "yes".   Eg.   User: Give me a list of all the projects?  System:   List of projects.  Would you like to know more about the technologies used?  User: Okay.

CONTENT: Short answer: yes. Ollama can store and run models from any folder â€” including an external drive â€” by pointing it to that location.  The two easy ways  Option A â€” change Ollamaâ€™s models directory (recommended)  Set the OLLAMA_MODELS environment variable to a folder on your external drive, then restart Ollama. 	â€¢	Windows 10/11 	1.	Create a folder on the external drive, e.g. E:\ollama-models 	2.	System â†’ Advanced system settings â†’ Environment Variablesâ€¦ â†’ Newâ€¦ (User variables) 	â€¢	Name: OLLAMA_MODELS 	â€¢	Value: E:\ollama-models 	3.	Quit and relaunch Ollama (or reboot). 	4.	Run ollama list to confirm models are visible. (Officially supported var; defaults are in C:\Users\<you>\.ollama\models if you donâ€™t change it.  ï¿¼) 	â€¢	macOS / Linux  # choose a folder on the external drive first, e.g. /Volumes/Ext/ollama-models export OLLAMA_MODELS="/Volumes/Ext/ollama-models"   # macOS # or on Linux: export OLLAMA_MODELS="/mnt/ext/ollama-models" # then (re)start the Ollama server ollama serve  (Ensure the ollama user has read/write on Linux, e.g. sudo chown -R ollama:ollama /mnt/ext/ollama-models.)  ï¿¼  From then on, pulls (e.g., ollama pull llama3) will download straight to that external folder.  Option B â€” move and symlink the original folder  If you already downloaded models, you can move the whole .ollama (or .ollama/models) directory to the external drive and create a symlink back to the original location. 	â€¢	Windows (PowerShell as Admin)  # Stop Ollama first # Move the folder C:\Users\<you>\.ollama to E:\.ollama  (use Explorer or Move-Item) cmd /c mklink /D "C:\Users\<you>\.ollama" "E:\.ollama"  ï¿¼ ï¿¼  	â€¢	macOS / Linux  # Stop Ollama; move ~/.ollama to external drive mv ~/.ollama /Volumes/Ext/.ollama          # macOS example ln -s /Volumes/Ext/.ollama ~/.ollama  (Same Linux permission note as above.)  ï¿¼  Tips for external drives 	â€¢	Speed matters: use a fast SSD over USB-C/Thunderbolt (or NVMe enclosure). Slow HDDs/USB2 will bottleneck loads and inference. 	â€¢	Formatting: use a native filesystem (APFS on macOS, NTFS on Windows, ext4 on Linux). exFAT works cross-platform but can be slower and less robust. 	â€¢	Always connect before launching Ollama: if the path isnâ€™t available, Ollama wonâ€™t find your models. 	â€¢	Housekeeping: ollama list to see sizes; ollama rm <model> to free space.  ï¿¼  If you tell me your OS (Windows/macOS/Linux), I can give you copy-paste commands tailored to your driveâ€™s actual path.
